Thanks to those who supported my question and tried your best to explain to a young Vietnamese-American about the past (history)which he as many others often very much confuse of its truefulness. By the way, I don't get offended easily, after all, this is just cyberpress.<br><br>
Going back to my question, unlike many young Vietnamese-Americans who don't care much of the past and most of the time they try their best to avoid it, but I do care deeply because I am very proud of being a Vietnamese-American.  I also believe that sad history need to be learned so it wouldn't repeat.<br><br>
There many books written by former Vietnamese Generals such as General Nguyen Chanh Thi (his book-Mot Doi Tam Su-an essay of a life time), who played very important roles in Ngo Dinh Diem period, clearly statetd that IT WAS A DIRECT ORDER FROM CIA.  <br><br>
Unfortunately, most of these books were written in Vietnamese.  Now who would you believe? The insiders or the outsiders?.  The eyewittness or the defendent?  Ofcourse, the U.S.government would deny any of such allegation.  History fact.....The CIA have always been denied of Fidel Casto's allegation that the CIA tried to assascinate him several times...until recently...what Fidel said was true...proved by the declassified documents released.<br><br>
I am here to say it was wrong or right to have him and his family killed....I just want you all to know that after his death, many Vietnamese Catholics (ardent supporter of him)were disappointed of U.S.policy.  Many of them turned agaisnt U.S. <br><br>
I think if we just confined him, it would have been better.  Oh, by the way....it was a big help to the North Vietnam's government in their propaganda agaisnt U.S. &quot; Ngo Dinh Diem was killed because he planed to reconsile with us.  He wanted a United Vietnam.  That why they killed him&quot;<br><br>
